WEBVTT

00:04.872 --> 00:05.839 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Good evening.

00:05.873 --> 00:06.840 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm Gwen Ifill.

00:06.874 --> 00:07.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I'm Judy
Woodruff.

00:07.875 --> 00:08.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: On the "NewsHour"
tonight:

00:08.876 --> 00:10.644 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

00:10.677 --> 00:11.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICK SCOTT (R), Florida: If
you're watching
and living in an evacuation
zone, you need

00:11.845 --> 00:13.580 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to leave now.

00:13.614 --> 00:17.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: A state of emergency
in Florida,
Georgia and South Carolina, as
the deadly

00:17.985 --> 00:21.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Hurricane Matthew gains
strength, barreling
toward the U.S.

00:21.855 --> 00:26.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Then, in our
series on the
issues shaping this election, we
take a look

00:26.927 --> 00:30.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at where the candidates stand
and differ on
guns.

00:30.530 --> 00:35.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And Jeffrey Brown
sits down with
the master of horror, Stephen
King, to talk

00:35.535 --> 00:38.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about his new novel and the art
of writing.

00:38.171 --> 00:40.641 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN KING, Author, "End of
Watch": I got
where the story leads.

00:40.674 --> 00:44.711 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And sometimes it's a little bit
outrageous.

00:44.745 --> 00:45.846 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I relish that.

00:45.879 --> 00:49.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I sort of want to be as much on
the edge as
I can.

00:49.917 --> 00:57.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more
on tonight's
"PBS NewsHour."

00:57.424 --> 01:00.193 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:00.227 --> 01:09.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It keeps coming
closer and getting
stronger.

01:09.436 --> 01:15.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hurricane Matthew's winds are
back up to 140
miles an hour as it plows toward
Florida tonight,

01:15.275 --> 01:23.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in its wake, up to 140 dead,
nearly all of
them in the island nation of
Haiti.

01:23.483 --> 01:28.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
From the skies above
Southwestern Haiti, the
destruction looks complete.

01:28.855 --> 01:33.293 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Entire neighborhoods have been
wiped out in
Jeremie, the region's main city.

01:33.327 --> 01:37.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): All
the money we
had has been lost.

01:37.197 --> 01:38.165 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Everything is lost.

01:38.198 --> 01:39.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We're lost.

01:39.199 --> 01:40.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We don't know.

01:40.534 --> 01:43.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We could see the destruction,
and we asked
for help, but no.

01:43.670 --> 01:48.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Aid workers are
finally getting
to some of the most heavily
damaged areas,

01:48.976 --> 01:51.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and they're reporting near total
losses.

01:51.845 --> 01:56.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Holly Frew with the aid
organization CARE
is monitoring the situation from
the Haitian

01:56.583 --> 01:58.318 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
capital of Port-au-Prince.

01:58.352 --> 02:03.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HOLLY FREW, CARE: About 80
percent of the
buildings and homes are damaged
or destroyed

02:04.024 --> 02:05.258 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in that area.

02:05.292 --> 02:07.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Everyone is kind of in a state
of shock.

02:07.461 --> 02:12.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's just utter devastation in
that western
side of southern bluff where the
hurricane

02:12.766 --> 02:14.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
eye just took a direct hit.

02:14.701 --> 02:20.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Despite the sweeping
destruction,
Tim Callaghan with the U.S.
Agency for International

02:20.640 --> 02:24.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Development, is holding out hope
that the
human cost may be less than
feared.

02:24.311 --> 02:25.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIM CALLAGHAN, USAID: The damage
observed
from the air was structural
damage and not

02:25.312 --> 02:27.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
heavy rain damage.

02:27.147 --> 02:33.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A lot of people were not
observed in the aerial
overflight, which would indicate
that people

02:33.453 --> 02:37.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were in shelters or people were
in homes.

02:37.791 --> 02:43.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Eastern Cuba is also
assessing
damage from the hurricane's
passage, and,

02:43.363 --> 02:45.799 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
overnight, the storm blew
through the Bahamas,
too.

02:45.832 --> 02:50.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. mainland is the next
target, with
Matthew expected to blast north
along the

02:50.971 --> 02:55.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
entire length of Florida's
Atlantic Coast
beginning tonight.

02:55.742 --> 03:00.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After that, it's likely to rake
Georgia and
South Carolina, before weakening
and veering

03:00.247 --> 03:01.848 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out to sea.

03:01.882 --> 03:06.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Overall, about two million
people in those
states are being warned to flee.

03:06.686 --> 03:07.854 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

03:07.888 --> 03:09.923 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
RICK SCOTT (R), Florida:
Evacuate, evacuate,
evacuate.

03:09.956 --> 03:14.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Florida Governor
Rick Scott was
out early and often today,
telling people

03:14.394 --> 03:15.362 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to leave.

03:15.395 --> 03:16.730 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

03:16.763 --> 03:18.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICK SCOTT: Are you willing to
take a chance
to risk your life?

03:18.465 --> 03:19.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Are you willing to take a
gamble?

03:20.000 --> 03:22.636 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's what you're doing.

03:22.669 --> 03:27.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you're reluctant to evacuate,
just think
of all the people this storm has
already killed.

03:27.174 --> 03:31.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Many heeded the
warnings, as heavy
rain began falling in Miami.

03:31.978 --> 03:36.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Interstate highways across the
region were
turned into one-way routes to
speed the exodus.

03:36.983 --> 03:40.320 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: I'm thinking just to get as
far away
from the flood zone as possible.

03:40.353 --> 03:44.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Others hastily
boarded up homes
and businesses, and thousands
checked into

03:45.025 --> 03:46.860 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
shelters.

03:46.893 --> 03:51.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: It's too risky to stay,
and just wanted
to stay safe and really hope we
have the grace

03:51.965 --> 03:53.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to accept the aftermath.

03:53.834 --> 03:58.472 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: You cannot replace your
child's life
or your mom's life or your
kid's, dad's, anybody's

03:58.505 --> 04:00.006 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
life.

04:00.040 --> 04:01.074 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Things are material.

04:01.108 --> 04:02.843 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can always replace your
things.

04:02.876 --> 04:07.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And whether they
were going or
staying, people everywhere
flocked to buy

04:07.314 --> 04:09.883 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
gasoline, food and water.

04:09.916 --> 04:15.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The threat of Matthew is also
forcing widespread
cancellations and closures of
everything from

04:15.856 --> 04:20.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
college football to theme parks
to airline
routes.

04:20.093 --> 04:24.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This afternoon, President Obama
declared a
state of emergency for Florida
and ordered

04:24.164 --> 04:27.334 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
federal aid to help on
the-ground efforts
there.

04:27.367 --> 04:32.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Federal Emergency Management
Agency, or
FEMA, has deployed people and
supplies there

04:32.038 --> 04:34.141 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and to Georgia and the
Carolinas.

04:34.174 --> 04:39.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I spoke to the agency
administrator coordinating
the federal response, Craig
Fugate, from FEMA

04:39.679 --> 04:41.281 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
headquarters late this
afternoon.

04:41.314 --> 04:45.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I began by asking how FEMA
prepares for such
a massive storm.

04:45.452 --> 04:47.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG FUGATE, Administrator,
Federal Emergency
Management Agency: Well, we
basically get

04:47.754 --> 04:52.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ready based on the storm track,
potential
impacts and looking at four
states.

04:52.993 --> 04:57.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we divided up teams to go
into each of
the state emergency operation
centers, and

04:57.330 --> 05:02.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we have set up some supply bases
that can
support multiple states, so we
can shift to

05:02.502 --> 05:04.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wherever the heaviest impacts
are.

05:04.337 --> 05:07.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have been getting ready
for the storm
for the last couple of days,
just like a lot

05:07.574 --> 05:10.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of the states and local
governments have been
doing, before this storm makes
impact.

05:10.377 --> 05:15.148 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, you have been
trying to preposition
resources in places where they
might be needed.

05:15.182 --> 05:19.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you tell where that is,
the places
that might be -- it might be
needed, but might

05:19.486 --> 05:22.923 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
also be the hardest-hit part of
the impact?

05:22.956 --> 05:25.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG FUGATE: Well, part of it
is looking
at the overall track guidance to
making some

05:25.892 --> 05:30.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
decisions about, where can we
move things
close to, but not in the area of
impact, and

05:30.830 --> 05:33.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then shift it as we get more
information on
the storm track.

05:33.900 --> 05:37.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, right now, we have moved
stuff into Albany
and Fort Bragg.

05:37.204 --> 05:42.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Working with the state of
Florida, we're actually
moving stuff down to their
operations center

05:42.175 --> 05:44.211 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where they have a big logistics
base in Orlando.

05:44.244 --> 05:50.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we try to move as the storm
shifts to just
stay outside of the heavy-hit
areas, but close

05:50.550 --> 05:53.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough where we're going to be
able to get
in quickly to support the state
and local

05:53.820 --> 05:55.589 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
responders.

05:55.622 --> 05:58.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What do you do when
the governor
of a state, for instance, of
Florida, said

05:58.825 --> 06:01.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
evacuate, evacuate, evacuate,
and people don't
do it?

06:01.528 --> 06:05.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG FUGATE: Well, I have been
in that role
at the state level and at the
local level.

06:05.966 --> 06:07.801 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that's one of our
challenges.

06:07.834 --> 06:11.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's one of the things you
can help,
explaining to people, showing
them the hazards.

06:11.271 --> 06:15.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think people understand we
don't have
enough certainty of track
forecast to tell

06:15.208 --> 06:17.444 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people, you're not going to be
at risk or
you're at risk.

06:17.477 --> 06:20.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have to warn the area based
upon the forecast.

06:20.380 --> 06:24.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And sometimes it's not that bad,
and that's
actually good, because you can
go back home.

06:24.718 --> 06:28.989 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But if it is as bad as
forecasted, I have
actually listened to the 911
calls.

06:29.022 --> 06:33.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There will be a point tonight
where it's too
late, people cannot be rescued,
they didn't

06:33.860 --> 06:36.363 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go in time, they're going to run
out of options.

06:36.396 --> 06:39.132 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, unfortunately, that means
they may lose
their lives.

06:39.165 --> 06:41.635 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is all about life safety.

06:41.668 --> 06:45.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's why we're so adamant
about getting
people to evacuate out of these
areas.

06:45.238 --> 06:48.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, yes, if it's not bad, go
back home.

06:48.408 --> 06:49.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But you have something to go
back to.

06:49.776 --> 06:52.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We can always rebuild, but we
cannot replace
lives lost.

06:52.379 --> 06:56.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What about coastal
infrastructure
like NASA launch pads, for
instance?

06:56.683 --> 06:59.486 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's right at the center of
the potential
hit zone.

06:59.519 --> 07:01.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CRAIG FUGATE: Well, we have a
lot of critical
infrastructure.

07:02.022 --> 07:02.989 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You have NASA.

07:03.023 --> 07:04.891 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have several military bases.

07:04.924 --> 07:06.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
You have the Port of
Jacksonville.

07:06.793 --> 07:09.362 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You have Port Canaveral.

07:09.396 --> 07:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of things that
have not been
through hurricane conditions in
a very long

07:13.466 --> 07:16.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
time, if ever, for the life of
those structures.

07:16.436 --> 07:19.572 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, again, we get ready for the
impacts.

07:19.606 --> 07:25.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We expect to have substantial
damage if that
eye wall is coming ashore at a
Category 4

07:25.211 --> 07:27.013 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or Category 3.

07:27.047 --> 07:29.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we can't really do much
about that right
now.

07:29.482 --> 07:33.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we can do is get people to
safety and
then be prepared to respond
afterwards to

07:33.586 --> 07:35.388 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
begin the response.

07:35.422 --> 07:40.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: What have you
learned from past
disasters like Hurricane Hugo, I
think, 1989,

07:40.493 --> 07:42.195 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that prepares you for now?

07:42.228 --> 07:46.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG FUGATE: Well, one of the
things you
will see along this part of the
coast is,

07:46.733 --> 07:51.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as you get further north, storm
surge values
will now go -- I think you're
seeing in a

07:51.204 --> 07:53.206 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
lot of areas 10 to 12 feet.

07:53.239 --> 07:56.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you move into the Carolinas,
particularly
South Carolina and Northern
Georgia, it even

07:56.776 --> 07:58.578 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
gets higher.

07:58.611 --> 08:02.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the things we saw in
Hurricane Hugo
is how far inland storm surge
can go, in some

08:02.982 --> 08:08.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cases over 30 feet of water that
went in miles
and flooded communities that
didn't even think

08:08.355 --> 08:10.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they were on the coast.

08:10.156 --> 08:13.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's why it's important that
people heed
those evacuation orders,
particularly around

08:13.827 --> 08:18.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rivers and the tributaries like
the St. John's,
the St. Mary's, up through the
Savannah River

08:18.798 --> 08:23.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and all those basins, because
water can travel
far inland and cause flooding
well away from

08:23.536 --> 08:25.305 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the coast, if people aren't
aware of it.

08:25.338 --> 08:30.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Which is more
dangerous, or is
it possible to quantify it, the
actual landfall

08:30.443 --> 08:32.345 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or the surge that you're talking
about?

08:32.379 --> 08:36.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CRAIG FUGATE: If you go back in
history, the
most deadly parts of the
hurricane has been

08:36.649 --> 08:38.385 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
water.

08:38.418 --> 08:42.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the majority of that and the
large loss
of life has been due to storm
surge events

08:42.856 --> 08:44.657 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
followed by heavy rainfall.

08:44.691 --> 08:49.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Wind is actually not as deadly
as people think
it is, although they tend to
look at the wind

08:49.129 --> 08:51.498 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
field and look at that as a
risk.

08:51.531 --> 08:56.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What has historically killed
people in past
from hurricanes has been water,
storm surge.

08:56.503 --> 08:59.939 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That coastal flooding has been
the leading
cause of death.

08:59.973 --> 09:03.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's why we're so adamant
about getting
people to evacuate.

