34:15.921 --> 34:25.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GAVIN SCHMIDT: Well, so, what's
happening
is that we are already a
geological force

34:25.430 --> 34:27.198 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on the climate.

34:27.232 --> 34:31.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, the fingerprint of
human activity
on the climate, not just in
carbon dioxide,

34:31.102 --> 34:35.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but in many, many other aspects,
is very,
very clear.

34:35.774 --> 34:40.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The agreements like the Paris
agreement and
efforts that are going on not
just at the

34:40.545 --> 34:46.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
national, but at the state and
city and individual
levels, are attempts to kind of
make that

34:46.885 --> 34:50.956 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not quite as large an impact as
we have already
had.

34:50.989 --> 34:53.291 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But it's a tough vote.

34:53.325 --> 35:00.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, to stabilize, so just to
keep carbon
dioxide levels at the same level
in perpetuity,

35:00.765 --> 35:04.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
