emissions by 80 percent
globally.

35:04.436 --> 35:08.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's a huge task, and it's not
something
that's going to be accomplished
today, or

35:08.406 --> 35:10.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tomorrow or in one electoral
cycle.

35:10.442 --> 35:15.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, at a time,
Mr. Schmidt,
when I think many of us
certainly in the United

35:15.447 --> 35:23.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States are focused on this big
hurricane heading
for the United States mainland,
this has to

35:23.421 --> 35:27.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
give -- and we know scientists
have spoken
about this, these big storms,
the concern

35:27.425 --> 35:29.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that they're going to get even
bigger.

35:29.227 --> 35:31.062 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GAVIN SCHMIDT: Right.

35:31.096 --> 35:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How should
Americans and others
think about climate change in
the face of

35:35.367 --> 35:36.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
something like this?

35:36.668 --> 35:39.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GAVIN SCHMIDT: So, one of the
key things is
sea level rise.

35:39.838 --> 35:46.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, sea level has risen about 10
foot, is
actually rising faster on the
Eastern Seaboard

35:46.344 --> 35:48.079 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than elsewhere.

35:48.113 --> 35:53.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For every extra foot of sea
level rise, a
storm surge, even if the climate
of storms

35:53.852 --> 35:57.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
doesn't change, the storm surge
has more damage.

35:57.455 --> 36:01.726 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is many, many thresholds,
that, you
know, if the water rises five
foot, you're

36:01.760 --> 36:07.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fine, but if it goes up six
feet, then it
overtops a levee, it over -- it
floods a subway.

36:07.132 --> 36:09.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It has much greater damages.

36:09.534 --> 36:16.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, sea level rise is one of
those aspects
of change that multiply the
damages that are

36:16.041 --> 36:22.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
caused by just the natural
variation of climate
and the natural variation of
hurricanes and

36:22.280 --> 36:24.082 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
storms that we see.

36:24.115 --> 36:30.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Plus, we have some expectation
that hurricanes
themselves and storms themselves
will become

36:30.055 --> 36:34.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more intense, perhaps less
frequent, but more
intense, and then that,
obviously, adds to

36:34.859 --> 36:36.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the damages as well.

36:36.961 --> 36:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's an
occasion to think
about all of this and to think
about the interconnection.

36:41.766 --> 36:45.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Gavin Schmidt with the Goddard
Institute for
Space Studies, we thank you.

36:45.437 --> 36:50.442 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GAVIN SCHMIDT: Thank you very
much.

