seeds for some
of this epidemic that we have
today.

37:28.146 --> 37:29.848 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
How so?

37:29.881 --> 37:35.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG, STAT: Well, the
way they
sowed the seeds was by making
this drug widely

37:35.053 --> 37:36.688 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
used.

37:36.721 --> 37:40.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the way they did that was to
downplay
the addictive properties of this
drug when

37:40.992 --> 37:46.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
marketing it to doctors, in a
way that was
later shown to be false and
misleading.

37:46.097 --> 37:50.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, doctors
can prescribe
drugs off-label for something
that it wasn't

37:50.902 --> 37:55.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
originally designed to, but how
were the pharma
companies abusing this?

37:55.373 --> 38:00.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Well, they were
primarily
abusing it in the way they were
assuring doctors

38:00.678 --> 38:07.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that these powerful opioids that
are a controlled
substance would not be addictive
in the way

38:07.585 --> 38:12.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they later proved to be
addictive and
could be used for things like
chronic pain,

38:12.757 --> 38:15.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which we now know they're not
very effective
at.

38:15.860 --> 38:21.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So they were able to broaden the
market through
a series of misrepresentations
and through

38:21.799 --> 38:23.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a series of aggressive marketing
tactics.

38:23.701 --> 38:25.637 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How much money
are we talking
about?

38:25.670 --> 38:27.005 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What did they stand to gain?

38:27.038 --> 38:30.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Well, let's
just look at
OxyContin.

38:30.975 --> 38:37.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When that came on the market in
1996, sales
of the drug were about $50
million.

38:37.115 --> 38:43.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By 2002, sales of this drug were
$1.6 billion,
and they have continued at that
clip ever

38:43.955 --> 38:47.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
since, exceeding well over $30
billion in
sales.

38:47.358 --> 38:48.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's just one drug.

38:48.860 --> 38:53.598 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So that gives you an idea of the
scale here
of the amount of money involved.

38:53.631 --> 38:58.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You were also
able to take
a look at documents through
Freedom of Information

38:58.269 --> 39:06.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Act requests that were sealed
that show how
these drugs were being marketed.

39:06.311 --> 39:07.278 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Explain that.

39:07.312 --> 39:09.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Yes.

39:09.314 --> 39:13.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, one of the interesting
things is, in the
case of OxyContin, Purdue
Pharma, which manufactures

39:13.484 --> 39:19.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the drug, and its partner in
marketing at
Abbott Laboratories, they were
sued over 1,000

39:19.591 --> 39:24.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
times collectively for problems
related to
this drug.

39:24.462 --> 39:29.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in a lot of those cases, in
fact, the
vast majority of them, the
documents involved

39:29.167 --> 39:32.437 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in those cases were either
destroyed or sealed.

39:32.470 --> 39:36.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we have been trying to unseal
some of those
in several jurisdictions, and we
have been

39:36.474 --> 39:38.109 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
successful.

39:38.142 --> 39:41.813 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in West Virginia, for
instance, we saw
some of the tactics that Abbott
used.

39:41.846 --> 39:45.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They did things like a
dine-and-dash program.

39:45.250 --> 39:50.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is where they would meet a
doctor at
a restaurant, pay for his
takeout order, and

39:50.121 --> 39:54.859 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
while waiting to pay for the
order, sell him
on the benefits of OxyContin.

39:54.892 --> 39:59.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then we wrote about a
doctor, a surgeon
who had a sweet tooth, a
fondness for junk

39:59.264 --> 40:01.132 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
food.

40:01.165 --> 40:05.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And these salespeople brought
him a sheet
cake filled with donuts and
snack cakes spelled

40:05.036 --> 40:07.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
out to say OxyContin.

40:07.372 --> 40:09.140 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that did the trick.

40:09.173 --> 40:12.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was interested in hearing
more about the
drug at that point, and they
would go back

40:12.410 --> 40:15.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
every week and get him to switch
patients
over to OxyContin.

40:15.813 --> 40:17.248 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Those are just a few of the
things.

40:17.282 --> 40:19.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And the sales
reps were
rewarded for these tactics?

40:19.717 --> 40:22.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Very
generously.

40:22.120 --> 40:24.822 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were rewarded with luxury
trips.

40:24.856 --> 40:31.629 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were $20,000 scratch
tickets that were
sent out to them as rewards.

40:31.663 --> 40:36.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the compensation was very
lucrative to
get these doctors to switch
patients to these

40:36.968 --> 40:38.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
powerful opioids.

40:38.636 --> 40:43.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There are
people who do
need significant pain
medications.

40:43.574 --> 40:46.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, they're the ones who
kind of get the
short end of the stick as this
abuse happens.

40:46.844 --> 40:49.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's the government's role in
oversight
of this?

40:49.781 --> 40:54.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Well, you're
now seeing,
because we're dealing with a
public health

40:54.385 --> 41:00.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crisis -- we have tens of
thousands of people
dying each year now from these
overdoses.

41:00.625 --> 41:05.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're seeing governments, state
governments
in particular, move to restrict
the prescription,

41:05.863 --> 41:10.301 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
primarily in making sure that
prescriptions
are a limited number of days.

41:10.335 --> 41:14.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before, they would be 30, 60
days, and there
would be plenty of pills left
over.

41:14.706 --> 41:15.907 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And those would get misused.

41:15.940 --> 41:19.744 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So that's one way, and also
educating prescribers.

41:19.777 --> 41:25.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Nobody wants to see a
prohibition of painkillers
for people who need them, but
one of the keys

41:25.616 --> 41:30.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is to make sure doctors are
educated in who
truly need them and they are
prescribing the

41:30.288 --> 41:32.023 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
right amount and the right drug.

41:32.056 --> 41:35.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
David Armstrong
of STAT joining us from Boston,
thanks so

41:35.426 --> 41:36.394 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
much.

41:36.427 --> 41:39.897 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Thank you.

41:39.931 --> 41:53.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: He is the author of
"Carrie,"
"The Shining, "Misery," and so
many more classic

41:53.444 --> 41:55.380 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and frightening tales.

41:55.413 --> 42:00.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the latest addition to the
"NewsHour" Bookshelf,
Stephen King, master of the
supernatural and

42:00.518 --> 42:04.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
suspense, reflects on the art of
writing and
his latest novel, "End of
Watch."

42:04.956 --> 42:08.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He spoke with Jeffrey Brown
recently at the
National Book Festival here in
Washington

42:08.726 --> 42:11.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: "End of Watch,"
the end of
a trilogy, right?

42:11.963 --> 42:13.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN KING, Author, "End of
Watch": Yes.

42:13.664 --> 42:16.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Does a trilogy
start life as
a trilogy?

42:16.734 --> 42:18.035 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: That's a very good
question.

42:18.069 --> 42:19.771 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Actually, no.

42:19.804 --> 42:26.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I thought that the first book in
the trilogy,
"Mr. Mercedes," would be the
only book.

42:26.477 --> 42:31.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I kind of didn't want to let
the characters
go, the main characters.

42:31.382 --> 42:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I had an idea for another
book, and realized
when I was working on that that
I had unfinished

42:37.488 --> 42:38.890 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
business from the first book.

42:38.923 --> 42:41.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I had a nice rounded quality,
the three
of them.

42:41.692 --> 42:44.495 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So you didn't
know where you
were heading, right?

42:44.529 --> 42:49.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, did you know -- even
when you start
a character in the first book,
Mr. Mercedes,

42:49.600 --> 42:51.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do you know where that was
going?

42:51.135 --> 42:52.737 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: No, I didn't.

42:52.770 --> 42:53.738 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

42:53.771 --> 42:54.739 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: ... with you?

42:54.772 --> 42:56.507 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You don't know where -- you
don't know?

42:56.541 --> 43:01.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: I very rarely --
sometimes,
I have an idea of how the book
will finish

43:01.813 --> 43:06.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up, but it very rarely finishes
up the way
that I think it's going to.

43:06.584 --> 43:08.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have to go where the book
leads you.

43:08.052 --> 43:09.020 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

43:09.053 --> 43:10.855 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And what about a character?

43:10.888 --> 43:16.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: There is a
novelist called Thomas
Williams, who's passed on now,
and he said

43:16.661 --> 43:22.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that the idea for a novel is
like a little
tiny fire in a dark night.

43:22.567 --> 43:26.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, one by one, the characters
come and stand
around it and warm their hands.

43:26.804 --> 43:30.541 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have always thought that's
the perfect
metaphor for how it works.

43:30.575 --> 43:32.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Come around
together and warm
their hands.

43:32.577 --> 43:33.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: They stand around
the fire.

43:33.945 --> 43:35.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And little by little, the fire
grows.

43:35.880 --> 43:37.648 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And you see them more clearly.

43:37.682 --> 43:38.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's the novel.

43:39.016 --> 43:39.984 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And the story
grows.

43:40.017 --> 43:41.752 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: Yes.

43:41.786 --> 43:46.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You wrote a very
lovely book
that I read years ago on writing
about your

43:46.591 --> 43:49.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
own life and the craft of
writing.

43:49.727 --> 43:54.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you wrote in there, "The
writer's original
perception of a character or
characters may

43:54.632 --> 43:56.801 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
be as erroneous as the
reader's."

43:56.834 --> 43:58.236 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: Right.

43:58.269 --> 43:59.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, this is the
sense of what
you're talking about.

43:59.770 --> 44:01.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: It is.

44:01.272 --> 44:03.407 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Here's an example of that.

44:03.441 --> 44:11.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a character in "Mr.
Mercedes," the
first book of the Hodges
Trilogy, a woman

44:11.115 --> 44:12.917 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
named Holly Gibney.

44:12.950 --> 44:17.255 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And as far as I was concerned,
she was just
going to be a walk-on character.

44:17.288 --> 44:19.090 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She's going to come on.

44:19.123 --> 44:22.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She's going to be a little
neurotic, and there
is going to be some discussion
with him.

44:22.126 --> 44:26.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then she was going to
disappear from view,
a minor character.

44:26.564 --> 44:29.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, instead, she came in and
took over the
whole book.

44:29.934 --> 44:34.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I let her because that's
what needed to
happen.

44:34.138 --> 44:38.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The worst thing you can try to
do is to steer
the story once it gets going.

44:38.342 --> 44:40.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You just kind of follow along
and see where
it goes.

44:40.978 --> 44:41.946 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's the fun.

44:41.979 --> 44:42.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That's the fun of
it.

44:42.980 --> 44:43.948 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: That's the fun of
it, yes.

44:43.981 --> 44:45.149 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And it still is
fun for you?

44:45.182 --> 44:48.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: Not every day, but
most days,
it is, yes.

44:48.386 --> 44:50.288 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I go where the story leads.

44:50.321 --> 44:54.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, sometimes, it is a little
bit outrageous.

44:54.425 --> 44:55.526 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I relish that.

44:55.560 --> 45:00.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I sort of want to be as much on
the edge as
I can.

45:00.498 --> 45:02.199 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I want to engage the reader.

45:02.233 --> 45:10.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm an emotional writer, in the
sense that
I would be happy if you re-read
a book for

45:11.008 --> 45:16.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the intellectual or the mental
part of it,
but, the first time, I just like
to reach

45:16.914 --> 45:19.517 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
out and grab you, pull you in.

45:19.550 --> 45:23.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You know, another
thing that
struck me, again going back to
the book on

45:23.087 --> 45:27.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
writing, you say: "Let's get one
thing clear
right now, shall we?

45:27.925 --> 45:34.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is no idea dump, no
central story, no
island of buried bestsellers,"
which is to

45:34.532 --> 45:40.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say that stories almost come
from just out
there, right?

45:40.838 --> 45:43.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And your job is to, what, find
them?

45:43.274 --> 45:46.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: I don't think you
find them,
exactly.

45:46.410 --> 45:50.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think what you do is, you keep
your sensors
open.

45:50.414 --> 45:57.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's -- the more that you do
the job,
the more you come to understand
in a kind

45:57.788 --> 46:03.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of intuitive way that you're
always -- you
know, your radar is on.

46:03.894 --> 46:06.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the thing is going around
and around and
around.

46:06.631 --> 46:08.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's not picking up any
blips.

46:08.933 --> 46:16.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then something will happen,
and it will
click, and you will say, this is
an idea for

46:16.040 --> 46:17.808 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
a story.

46:17.842 --> 46:22.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, for me, I'm usually working
on something,
so that's kind of got to go to
the end of

46:22.113 --> 46:23.848 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the line.

46:23.881 --> 46:28.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the best thing about that
is, is that
the bad ideas kind of just drop
out of the

46:28.285 --> 46:29.253 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mix.

46:29.286 --> 46:30.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You forget about them.

46:30.287 --> 46:31.422 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The good ones stick around.

46:31.455 --> 46:32.923 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
So...

46:32.957 --> 46:38.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, does that
mean writing
can be taught, can be learned?

46:38.562 --> 46:42.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: It can be learned,
but I'm not
sure it can be taught.

46:42.633 --> 46:44.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a self-taught kind of
thing.

46:44.969 --> 46:54.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the best writers are
voracious readers
who pick up the cadences and the
feel of narration

46:54.612 --> 46:56.814 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
through a number of different
books.

46:56.847 --> 47:02.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you begin by maybe copying
the style of
writers that really knocked you
out.

47:02.219 --> 47:06.190 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, as a teenager, I read a
lot of H.P.

47:06.223 --> 47:07.925 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Lovecraft, so I wrote like H.P.

47:07.958 --> 47:09.727 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Lovecraft.

47:09.760 --> 47:14.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in my 20s, I read a lot of
Ross Macdonald
and Raymond Chandler, so I wrote
like those

47:14.632 --> 47:15.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
guys.

47:15.733 --> 47:17.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, little by little, you
develop your own
style.

47:17.902 --> 47:23.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You describe in
"On Writing"
book about learning the
discipline, even the

47:23.774 --> 47:27.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
place where you want to write,
things like
that?

47:27.211 --> 47:28.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: Yes.

47:28.379 --> 47:30.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a kind of self-hypnosis
involved with
it, too.

47:30.915 --> 47:38.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you start at the same time
every day -- most
writers have little routines
they go through.

47:38.089 --> 47:45.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I like to always stop with a
couple of pages
that I haven't -- that are just
raw copy,

47:45.596 --> 47:50.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where I haven't touched it, I
haven't tried
to revise it, I haven't tried to
polish it.

47:50.267 --> 47:52.336 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's like having a little bit of
a runway.

47:52.369 --> 47:56.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The next day when you sit down,
you have the
comfort of saying, well, I have
got a little

47:56.741 --> 47:58.876 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bit here, used to be in the
typewriter.

47:58.909 --> 48:00.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now it's in the magic box, the
computer.

48:00.678 --> 48:01.946 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: I see.

48:01.979 --> 48:05.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it's not an empty slate as
you start the
next day?

48:05.416 --> 48:08.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: Cold start is a
hard start.

48:08.486 --> 48:09.587 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:09.620 --> 48:12.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, let me ask
you one more
thing.

48:12.289 --> 48:16.560 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Can you imagine stopping
writing, not writing?

48:16.594 --> 48:21.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN KING: Well, when people
say, what
scares you, because I have
written a lot of

48:21.766 --> 48:22.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
horror novels.

48:22.867 --> 48:23.734 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You have written
some scary
novels.

48:23.768 --> 48:25.536 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: Yes.

48:25.569 --> 48:31.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I say, what really scares me is
Alzheimer's
or premature senility, losing
that ability

48:31.542 --> 48:34.145 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to read and enjoy and to write.

48:34.178 --> 48:39.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you do it, and some days
maybe aren't
so good, and then some days, you
really catch

48:39.784 --> 48:43.154 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a wave, and it's as good as it
ever was.

48:43.187 --> 48:46.490 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it's tough to imagine giving
it up.

48:46.524 --> 48:49.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Stephen King,
thank you very
much.

48:49.760 --> 48:55.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEPHEN KING: Thank you.

48:55.800 --> 48:57.568 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
