48:57.601 --> 49:04.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to another of
our Brief
But Spectacular series, where we
ask interesting

49:04.742 --> 49:06.610 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
people to share their passions.

49:06.644 --> 49:13.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from B.J.
Miller, a palliative
care doctor in the San Francisco
Bay Area.

49:13.584 --> 49:18.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He explains how working in end
of life care
can help inform the way we live.

49:18.923 --> 49:20.691 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

49:20.724 --> 49:22.226 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
B.J. ®MDNM /MILLER, Zen Hospice
Project:
When people find out I'm in
palliative care,

49:22.259 --> 49:26.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first of all, many people -- you
start with,
well, oh, well, what is that?

49:26.096 --> 49:32.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The interdisciplinary pursuit of
quality of
life, and the context is always
advanced or

49:32.870 --> 49:33.838 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
serious illness.

49:33.871 --> 49:35.139 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Palliative care is irrespective
of the clock.

49:35.172 --> 49:46.450 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You don't have to be dying
anytime soon.

49:46.483 --> 49:50.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The curiosity from the public
tends to be
-- and I hear this all the time
-- wow, you

49:50.187 --> 49:51.655 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
know, that must be so
depressing.

49:51.689 --> 49:55.426 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, you must be depressed
all the time.

49:55.459 --> 50:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not always happy, by a long
shot, but
there is this side effect that
seems to come.

50:02.766 --> 50:07.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
By facing mortality, it seems to
inform how
you live.

50:07.605 --> 50:14.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the secret is that facing
death has a
lot to do with living well.

50:14.211 --> 50:17.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The whole reason I went into
medicine was
because I became a patient.

50:17.214 --> 50:22.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In college, sophomore year, my
dear friends
and I were horsing around one
night.

50:23.020 --> 50:24.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We decided to climb a parked
train.

50:24.989 --> 50:29.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I happened to have a metal watch
on, and the
-- and, when I stood up, the
electricity arced

50:29.526 --> 50:31.662 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to the watch, and that was that.

50:31.695 --> 50:40.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was sort of an introduction
to my own death,
my own sense of mortality, my
own finiteness.

50:40.871 --> 50:45.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're the object of a lot of
sympathy, pity,
a lot of head-tilts.

50:45.276 --> 50:49.013 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At first, it's kind of sweet,
but then it
starts turning a little
saccharine.

50:49.046 --> 50:54.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You quickly look down that road,
and it's
not too long before you realize
that's a dead

50:54.084 --> 50:55.886 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
end.

50:55.920 --> 50:58.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's just another way of
removing yourself
or being removed from the flow
of society.

50:58.656 --> 51:04.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the ways that I got
through some of
the early days was insisting
that this was

51:04.495 --> 51:09.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a variation on a theme we all
experience,
and that theme is -- basically
is suffering.

51:09.333 --> 51:11.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some way, life is not going to
do what you
want it to do.

51:11.969 --> 51:14.305 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Your body is not going to do
what you want
it to do.

51:14.338 --> 51:15.306 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You will suffer.

51:15.339 --> 51:17.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's unavoidable.

51:17.308 --> 51:22.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there is this unnecessary
rind of suffering,
which is so -- which is the
demoralizing part,

51:22.212 --> 51:23.948 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
because it's the invented stuff.

51:23.981 --> 51:27.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It comes in terms of how we
treat each other,
sometimes poorly.

51:27.551 --> 51:30.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It comes in those moments of
abandonment.

51:30.354 --> 51:35.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We end up warehousing folks who
are sitting
on piles of wisdom and
experience and just

51:35.159 --> 51:37.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
plain hilarious or good stories.

51:37.294 --> 51:42.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we could sort of shift that a
little bit,
there's a lot more peace waiting
for all of

51:42.900 --> 51:44.668 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
us as we age.

51:44.702 --> 51:48.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think a lot of us are really
worried, not
so much about the fact that we
die, but how

51:48.872 --> 51:50.741 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we die.

51:50.774 --> 51:57.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Very often, patients themselves,
the people
doing the dying, will get to a
place of acceptance,

51:57.414 --> 52:00.250 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
beyond acceptance even, you
know, ready to
go.

52:00.284 --> 52:01.251 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You're done.

52:01.285 --> 52:03.020 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You're done with this body.

52:03.053 --> 52:06.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of the effort, my effort,
the team's
effort, the hospice
organization's effort,

52:06.457 --> 52:09.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is actually not so much on the
patient, the
person doing the dying.

52:09.927 --> 52:11.795 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's on the family.

52:11.829 --> 52:16.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a way, it's harder to accept
the death
of another person than accept
your own, especially

52:16.367 --> 52:19.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when you really love that
person.

52:19.403 --> 52:20.871 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm B.J. Miller.

52:20.904 --> 52:26.643 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And this is my Brief But
Spectacular take
on tying dying and living.

